Use [.pendingMocks][1], either on an individual scope or on the global Nock instance, to get a list of strings describing which `Interceptors` are not &quot;done&quot;.

    if (!scope.isDone()) {
      console.error(&#39;pending mocks: %j&#39;, scope.pendingMocks())
    }

It looks like you&#39;re using [Mocha][2], here is a snippet I use. This is in an `afterEach` on the global test runner.

    afterEach(function() {
      // https://github.com/mochajs/mocha/wiki/HOW-TO:-Conditionally-fail-a-test-after-completion
      if (this.test &amp;&amp; !lodash.has(this.test, &quot;ctx.currentTest.err&quot;)) {
        const pendingMocks = nock.pendingMocks();
        if (pendingMocks.length) {
          const msg = [&quot;Not all nock mocks were used:&quot;]
            .concat(pendingMocks)
            .join(&quot;\n\t&quot;);
          this.test.error(msg);
        }
      }
    
      nock.cleanAll();
    });

If the test has not already failed, and there are pending mocks still, then the test will receive an error listing all the pending Interceptors. [cleanAll][3] is then called to remove any persisted or optional mocks.


  [1]: https://github.com/nock/nock#pendingmocks
  [2]: https://mochajs.org/
  [3]: https://github.com/nock/nock#cleanall

