For axios to get a local file the path needs to be absolute. Best practice is to set this in an axios instance using the create method.

(Code direct from axios docs)

    const instance = axios.create({
      baseURL: &#39;https://some-domain.com/api/&#39;,
      timeout: 1000,
      headers: {&#39;X-Custom-Header&#39;: &#39;foobar&#39;}
    });

The baseurl would be the absolute url to the directory where your json files are. Then you can request them using axios get.

    instance.get(&#39;someFile.json&#39;)

A nice feature of doing it this way is that if you need to use axios get with a different url, the base url is only used when an absolute path is not used. So if later you use `axios.get(&#39;http://some-domain.com/some-end-point/)` the baseURL will automatically be ignored.

Using jq, you basically have two choices:

    echo $var | jq &#39;.. | .description?&#39;

or if you want to be more specific:

    echo $var | jq &#39;.result[] | .description?&#39;

But there are other variations ...

